segments.text: This is an interview with Dr. Larry Hickman by Kelly Wood on December 6, 1990, concerning the 60s movement.
In the interest of accumulating knowledge, I am asking you, Dr. Hickman, to donate this tape to the Texas A&M Oral History Collection in the University Archives.
Is this okay with you?
Sure.
Okay, great.
Now I guess we'll begin.
Where and when were you born?
I was born in October 6, 1942, in McAllen, Texas.
Why did you choose to attend Hardin-Simmons University?
I was interested in religious matters and religious studies and decided to go there because it had a program in religious studies that would be satisfactory to me.
I grew up in the Southern Baptist Church.
And although I wasn't interested in majoring in religion, I was interested in having access to some of the thinking in that area.
As an undergraduate at Hardin-Simmons between 1960 and 1964, what were the dorm rules and regulations like?
Dorm rules and regulations were different for male and female students, as I suppose they still are.
The dorm rules and regulations for men, basically, male students didn't have any particular hours they had to keep.
And in fact, apart from prohibitions against excessive noise, I suppose there weren't any regulations.
The female students had to be in by
11 o'clock on weeknights and 12 o'clock on weekends.
And apart from that, I don't know what their other prohibitions were.
Okay.
Was there a dress code?
There was no official dress code as far as dressing up.
At Hardin-Simmons in the 1960s, the female students were not allowed to wear slacks, Levi's, anything like that.
They had to wear dresses.
You wouldn't, in fact, although I don't think it was official, you wouldn't wear Bermuda shorts to class.
But as far as wearing a tie or something like that, that wasn't required.
It was a little more formal than now, but not terribly so.
Was drinking allowed?
There was no drinking allowed, not only on the campus at Hardin-Simmons, being a Baptist college, a Baptist university, but also Abilene was dry.
And in fact, it was only as I became a senior, I think, in 1964, did a local precinct go wet.
So during most of the time I was there, alcohol was not available, oh, within a 50-mile radius of Abilene.
Okay, thank you.
Were your grades sent home to your parents?
My grades were sent home to my parents, I believe.
It's hard to reach back that far to get that memory, but yeah, I think they were.
Okay, and when you attended University of Texas, did you still experience this in loco parenthesis?
No, the grades weren't sent, if that's what you're asking.
Grades were not sent to my parents when I was a graduate student at the University of Texas.
There were, of course, no dress codes.
I mean, you didn't, you could wear shorts to class if you felt like it.
And I didn't live in a dorm, so I don't know what the restrictions were then.

Certainly there was a much looser kind of atmosphere at the University of Texas, but it may just be accounted for by the fact that Hardin-Simmons was a small Baptist university of 1,800 students, and the University of Texas was a large state university of 18,000 students.
So it was an increase on the order of 10 in terms of the size of the university.
Was the draft an issue discussed in 1960 through 64?

Not very much, although I've got to admit that I thought about the military service a good bit, because when I reached Hardin-Simmons, I was shocked to learn that ROTC was required for all freshman and sophomore male students.
I hadn't known about that to that point, or I might have considered a different university.

In those days, the Southern Baptists made a big deal out of the fact that they didn't accept any foreign aid, any federal aid, to them it was foreign aid, but any federal aid from, well, any aid from the U.S. government, and therefore would be able to keep their universities pure from any kind of federal influence.
What they did, however, was they kind of pawned or
or hawked their freshman and sophomore students, made them take ROTC, and therefore collected a bounty of X dollars per head for every freshman and sophomore male student.
It was kind of a backdoor way of getting federal aid, and I was a pawn in that game.
A good many of my fellow students decided to take the junior and senior year of ROTC,
which meant they got a nice monthly stipend.
The only problem, of course, it wasn't a very big problem in 1963 or late 1962 or 1963 when they were deciding to do this, was that they would, in fact, have to spend two years in the Army.
But no one thought much about that in 1962-63.
There were some miscellaneous skirmishes going on in some place called Indochina, but nobody paid much attention to it.
Unfortunately, our class graduated in 1964, and some of the people who had thought they'd pursue a kind of a quiet, calm career
of a couple of maybe four years in the Army got some rather rude surprises.
In fact, some of them, by 1966, by the time they would have retired from the service, in 1968, were dead.
Did you fight in the Vietnam War?
No, I didn't fight in the Vietnam War.
I chose not to go into the advanced ROTC.
I didn't like the military discipline of the first two years.
and thought that there were better ways to spend my time.
And I never did...
I never did...
I saw no military service at all in the 60s.
How did you get out of serving in the war?
It was very complicated.
For the first thing, I mean, there were a whole series of circumstances.
The first thing is that I was married shortly before and therefore had what was then called
a 2A deferment shortly before President Johnson canceled the deferment.
It was really quite just happenstance that that deferment was canceled shortly after I was married.
So I had the 2A.
That, I had the feeling, would not have gotten me through the war.
I was also a 2S, which was a student deferment, and in fact was in graduate school for quite a number of years.
I mean, the standard amount of time one takes to pursue a Ph.D., which in my case was about six years.
And I have a feeling, however, that a much more important factor was that my draft board was in San Antonio.

And I have a feeling that I profited from the fact, that is, I benefited from the fact that there were lots of poor Hispanic males in San Antonio who could be drafted, and that they didn't have to dip into the pool of people who were in school quite so far, pursuing higher educations, quite so far in San Antonio because of the pool they had there.
That's a hunch.
I've never been able to document that, nor have I tried.
but it certainly is a reasonable hypothesis, I think.
Did you support the war?
At the very first, I suppose, in 1965, I thought that it was a good idea to, being rather naive about the history of the area,
I thought that a larger military presence was required and that the thing could have gotten over with rather quickly if there had been a larger commitment.
I had the good fortune, however, to, I was attending a Baptist church in Austin at the time, this was about 1965, and was, no, wait, I'm sorry, this is the fall, in fact, of 1964.
I was attending Baptist Church there near the university, which was, I suppose, the university church, really quite a liberal one by Southern Baptist standards.
And the assistant minister there, who was quite a liberal sort, asked me to conduct a discussion group on what was then called the Indochina question.
Being a person who felt the need to research
topics before I led discussion groups.
I went to the library and read a bunch of books on Indochina, on Vietnamese history.
I was especially interested in books by Bernard Fall, who had been a student of that part of the world for many years, a French correspondent, who in fact had an advanced degree in Indochina studies.
And during the course of that semester, as a matter of fact,
my views really changed from supporting the war to profound doubt that the war was winnable and that it was advisable.
I often thought later that if everybody in America had had the occasion to go to the library and read a few books on Vietnam, maybe things would have been a little different much earlier.
Why did you become against it?

Well, Bernard Fall and the other people who I read convinced me that it was a civil war, that the menace of communism was in fact not so much anything that was threatening to the United States as it was a kind of difference of opinion about the way that the Vietnamese should conduct their affairs.
and that the Vietnamese had no tradition of democracy such as we had in this country and they therefore were being presented in ways by the government and by the media that were pretty much false.
So I began to think that the problem was a
a local one rather than a global one.
I wasn't actively opposed to the war at that point, but I did have serious doubts about American involvement in it.
I wasn't by any means out demonstrating in 1964, and as far as I know, no one else was either.
But I began to take the issue very seriously, had discussions with my friends,
I still would not say I was a dove.
Some of my friends were.
In fact, some of my friends were much further to the left on that issue than I was at that point.
But at least it opened up ways of talking to people because I at least began to have an informed opinion as opposed to just an opinion.
What did you do besides discussion groups to be actively against it?
In 1964, not very much, because things were fairly low-key in 1964.
By the time the war began to heat up, we began to have demonstrations.
I don't remember the year this occurred, but I can remember being in one of the first, taking part in one of the first anti-war demonstrations in Austin.
It was a march up Congress Avenue from the river.
There couldn't have been more than 50 people, and there were people throwing things at us from the sidewalk.
The numbers are very small, and really we were considered a very radical group, although today it would not be considered terribly radical to do that.
There was difficulty getting parade permits for unpopular causes.
And in fact, that experience has really profoundly affected my views about the First Amendment and the importance of the First Amendment.
So that, for instance, later when the Klan wanted to march in Skokie, Illinois, I basically supported their right to do it, despite the fact that I think the Klan
a bunch of scum.
It seems to me that even scum are protected by the First Amendment.
So that was very formative.
To have people hurl epithets and physical objects at you for expressing your view was a very important experience.
What were your ideas on civil rights?
Well, civil rights was an issue which had been very much a part of the American scene
even when I was in college.
I wasn't involved very much in that in the 1960s because the issue was not really a big issue in Abilene, Texas.
Ethnic minorities in Abilene were a minimum.
There were very few blacks, and so, I mean, Abilene is really not a part of the South.
It's a part of the West, and so I suppose my
my interest in that.
I've got to also add that I really grew up in what might be called Mexican Texas or Hispanic Texas rather than the portions of Texas that had a good number of black people.
So I was really more aware of discrimination against Hispanics than aware of discrimination against blacks.
And therefore it really wasn't until
I went to Austin, and I began to be interested in that issue that really had been part of the American scene for some time.
When I moved to Austin in 1964, the Paramount Theater was still segregated.
The black people had to sit upstairs in the balcony, and there were demonstrations.
I didn't take part in any of those demonstrations, but I was aware of them and was very sympathetic toward the demonstrators.
Did a person have to have long hair and do drugs to be considered in during the 60s?
No, not at all.

Some of my best friends, in fact, in the SDS, the Students for a Democratic Society, had short hair and they wore sports coats and ties and didn't do drugs because they wanted to look as normal as possible, in quotes, so that they could have the greatest political effect.
So they thought of themselves as kind of wearing protective coloring, so to speak, in order to get their ideas out.
So that certainly would be false to say that.
And in fact, I don't think that long hair was by any means a badge of honor.
It seemed to me always just a matter of personal taste.
It may have, I mean, it certainly had to do something with the freedom to be different that was being expressed and kind of a reaction against the stereotypes that we'd grown up with.
But I don't know that it was, I don't know that it was for me ever a member of joining a club as it was just something different to try and see if I liked it.
What is your definition of a hippie?

Well, hippie is a term that was invented by Time Magazine, and if I could quote Joe Krupa, who's now the chair of the English department at the University of Texas, and who was a young hip faculty member when I was there, that probably has never been a hippie.
It's a term that was invented by Time Magazine and, like a lot of other words that purport to refer, I'm not sure it does.
What is clear is that there began to be alternate lifestyles expressed in the 1960s.
And if you want to call those people hippies, well, that's fine, but you just have to spend a lot of time defining your terms and say what you mean by it.
So I have no definition because I'm not sure the term really works very well.
So did you have your hair long?
I wore my hair long for quite a number of years.
And in fact, when I got a job at Texas A&M, my hair was probably almost as long as yours.
That means shoulder length.
Yes.
When did you first see people with these alternate lifestyles?
And what was your impression of them?
Well, Austin in 1964, 1965 was beginning to have people who, well actually I guess 65, 66 was beginning to have people who were in touch with friends on the West Coast.
There were people who had come from the West Coast, from the Berkeley area, to Austin in the mid-1960s, I guess around 1965.
And I remember the opening of the first Rock Palace, which was anything but a palace.
It was an old kind of dumpy storefront on Congress Avenue.
And what was the name of the place?
Well, I can't even remember now, but it was a place that
really had the first people with extremely long hair, I guess, that I'd seen.
Although that's not quite true.
Actually, people began to come through there, but as a matter of fact, in 1965 or 1966, I guess it was, a friend and I went, when was the Summer of Peace and Love?
I can't even remember now, whatever year that was, in Haight-Ashbury.
Some friends and I actually drove out to California to see what was going on, and of course there were several people with long hair and beads and love signs, peace signs, and so on then.
But gradually more and more people, there was always a lot of commerce between the West Coast and Austin, even before the 60s.
Austin was on the music scene, kind of the college music scene.

I mean, if you were going to make a tour, it would include not only Berklee and other places, but Austin, Little Rock, and so it was on that circuit that went from the west coast to the east coast and back.
I mean, there were a lot of people from the west coast coming in.
When you saw these people in California, what did you think of them?
I mean, did you laugh at them, or did you want to be a part of them?
No, by no means.
I was fascinated with the...
I mean, I've always been interested in things that were different, and so I've always thought that we don't have all the answers, no matter how we live or what we do.
So I was fascinated by the whole business.
I stayed in California for, I guess, a week or so, and met people, talked to people, and
I listened to some of the music that some of the groups out there were beginning to play.
I remember the first time I heard Country Joe and the Fish.
It was quite a wonderful experience.
I saw the cultural phenomenon as one that had a lot of interest, and who knows what it would do.
Could you define what a radical is?
Well, of course, the dictionary definition of a radical is someone who wants to go to the root of the matter.
And what that comes down to in any particular social and political unit or society is, well, it'll differ from society to society.
I suppose if you were...
a radical during the 1960s, it meant that you were deeply distrustful of the US government.
You felt you'd been lied to.
You felt that there was a basic unfairness about the way that minorities were being treated, about the way that you were being treated if you were up for the draft.
and that the government was no longer really responding to the problems that were apparent and that something radical or drastic needed to be done.
That took different forms for different people.
You said you joined SDS?
No, I never joined SDS.
I had a good number of friends in SDS, but I was never a member.
Why didn't you join SDS?
I was busy being a graduate student.
I didn't join anything, basically.
I wasn't a member of any clubs or groups when I was a graduate student.
I was working very hard.
It's not that I was in graduate school for a deferment.
I had a deferment because I was in graduate school.
Even though I was active politically in terms of supporting friends who were involved with political activities and involved myself in marches and did whatever I could, I saw the political
kind of thing that was going on as part of a broader cultural manifestation.
So I really didn't join any groups.
Why didn't you join these groups?
I really didn't have the time to be an active member of any of the groups.
I preferred to
be a part, that is, on the edge of several groups without actually getting into the organizational or administrative aspects of it.
I did not think that I had the time to be a leader in any kind of political or cultural manifestation because I was working very hard being a graduate student.
Well, when you look back on your years at the University of Texas, can you remember some of the radical events that you witnessed or participated in?
Oh, sure.
I can remember the radical events.
I guess you mean some of the things that really occurred either on a large scale that indicated satisfaction with the status quo or something of that sort.
I remember very clearly the day that the students demonstrated against the invasion of Cambodia.
And I don't remember the year.
We could look it up.
It must have been 67, 68, maybe.
Well, actually, it was later than that.
It was Nixon, so it would have to have been later, 69, 70.
The demonstrations against that formed a line of people

four or six abreast that started off by the Student Union Building in Austin, went all the way down to the Capitol, which is 12th Street, which is some eight or nine blocks away, and then came back up to the east side of the campus, to the Littlefield Fountain.
And there were so many people that by the time the first
bunch were getting to the fountain, the last bunch were just beginning to leave the student center.
And that's a lot of people.
I mean, one could estimate maybe 25,000 people marching that day.
That's quite remarkable.
I do remember other demonstrations at which I suppose the most dangerous one I witnessed was the

at the time that there were several speeches made on the steps of the administration building at the University of Texas, and there was one particular speaker who encouraged everybody to march on the state capitol.
And as it turned out, the administration got wind of that and posted a line of
Texas Rangers and DPS troopers at the base of the plaza there in front of the administration building.
They were heavily armed, and there were some very tense moments at that point.
I'm kind of a political pragmatist, and I thought that the calls for action that were advanced by some of my
fellow students were just a little bit foolish, and that the same kind of results could have been achieved by means that would not have the seeds of violence.
It seemed to me, even at the time, that violence was not a very good solution to any of the problems.
I mean, that's what we were against, right?
So that for people who were claiming that we should, quote, bring war home, I didn't have much sympathy for that.
Do you remember the LBJ library being built in a protest against that?
Yeah, sure.
In fact, there were protests against that.
There were protests against much of the building project that was going on during that time.
that was initiated by Frank Irwin, who was the head of the Board of Regents at that time.
The students and Frank Irwin didn't get along at all.
In fact, he called a group of them a bunch of dirty nothings at some point.
And that became a quite popular phrase around the university.
People were describing themselves as dirty nothings.
And yeah, I remember that.
And in fact, I was back at the University of Texas as a faculty member the day, the year that the LBJ Library was dedicated.
And I had an office overlooking, or with a view of the LBJ Library, I went up to go to work on
a Saturday, and there was a guy in a blue suit with sunglasses and saddle oxfords with a white button-down shirt telling me I couldn't go to my office.
Apparently my window had a little too clear a view of the place where LBJ was going to make his speech, so they just told me I'd have to come back later.
And did you?
I didn't argue with them.
When did you first think about women's liberation?
Well, that's difficult to answer because it's not real clear exactly when women's liberation began to be a term.
The history of the women's movement, of course, goes back a long way.
But if the question is,
When did I become aware that there were serious deficits in our society, serious deficiencies in our society regarding the way that women are treated?
I suppose that was also about the time that I was in Austin.
I didn't really think a whole lot about that when I was in Abilene because, well, things were very quiet in Abilene.
There really wasn't much stimulation to thinking.
you just kind of did your thing and you got your degree and there really wasn't much intellectual stimulation.

I began to be aware of that really much more from 1964 on, and I think partially as a consequence of meeting women and getting to know women who were dissatisfied with their situation and had legitimate gripes.
And it was really impossible not to have a great deal of sympathy and to come to see their side of things.
What did you think about women before their movement?
Before the...
I'm sorry.
Before the women's liberation movement.
What did you think?
Did you think that their place was in the home?
Or what did you think?
Well, I wouldn't say that I ever thought that.
But...

I would say I had a much more traditional view of matters, not necessarily that the woman's place should be in the home, but let's just say that I didn't see the possibilities for the kind of self-actualization of women in our society that I began to see later.
You've got to remember that Hardin-Simmons, for all of its faults, had a very strong tradition of women who went out and did things.
They were missionaries, and they were all kinds of religious leaders, and they didn't depend on a lot of men to help them do it.
So there was that strong tradition among the Southern Baptists that by George, if a young woman wanted to train to be a missionary in Nigeria, she'd
didn't particularly need the help of a young man to do it.
It would be nice if she could marry somebody who was interested in that sort of thing, but by gum, she could just go do it herself.
And so there was that dimension that was there even then.
What impact did Women's Lib have on your life?
Oh boy, that's a very large question.
And I guess it would be difficult to answer since it's
still going on.
To tell you the truth, I just don't even know how to answer the question.
I include components in my courses now on feminist issues and try to
be as sensitive as possible to the kinds of grievances that women in their society have.
I've been a member of the National Organization for Women for several years.
And apart from that, though, it would be very hard to sum up
that kind of changes in a brief time, because it's just been very extensive.
Do you foresee any of the 1960s idealism and freedom to do your own thing for the 1990s?
Well, I don't know if it's going to come in the 1990s or not.
I hope it will.
I hoped it would in the 1980s, and I hoped it would in the 1970s.
I hoped it would continue.
because I think idealism, especially among young people, is very good and that it's something that can be mobilized for great advantage.
But don't you think that it can let people down?
I mean, if you have idealism, then you can just kind of be let down?
Well, you certainly can, and I'm not sure there's anything that one does that doesn't allow for being let down at some point.
But it seems to me that...

During the 1960s, when young men and women were going off to the Peace Corps and they were getting into careers in academics that they thought were important, even though perhaps low-paying, and they believed that one should be aware of social issues and try to make a change for the better, and they were paying attention to Kennedy's famous remark that they should
ask what they could do for their country.

It seemed to me that that was a better time, certainly better one than a time during which the primary goal is to get a high-paying job immediately after college and to put blinders on in a way that makes one unaware of the social problems around one.
So I would welcome a new upthrust of
of idealism and hope that it wouldn't be too long before we saw it again.
What is the impact on the counterculture on American society?
Well, I think it's very profound.
And I think that there's a sense in which the 60s have really never receded.
America is a much more pluralistic place than it was prior to the 60s, not only ethnically in terms of the awareness that people have of other cultures.
I mean, we think of ourselves as a culture now in a way that we didn't before the 1960s.
We think of ourselves as a
as a society in which there are lots of different groups competing for all kinds of different things.
But prior to the 1960s, that perception was much smaller because it didn't include a lot of people that it includes now.
I think also in terms of the arts, in terms of lifestyles,
the freedom to pursue alternative lifestyles.
For instance, before the 1960s, you really didn't see very many people working out non-traditional ways of living together.
You didn't see

groups of people getting together and living together as you have recently begun to see in certain places like the West Coast among people who are, say, in their 60s or 70s for mutual aid and creating new kinds of families.
So my point here, then, is that a lot of different models were tried out in the 1960s, and some of them didn't work very well, and some of them
worked pretty well and they were retained and we still got a lot of that stuff going on now.
I think that the arts are much more open as a result of changes in the 1960s.
That we've learned some lessons, we learned some lessons in the 60s about freedom of expression and individual rights or individual liberties that we still haven't forgotten.
And there was an experimentalism then that we still retain important vestiges of.
The problem is that all of this kind of exists below a rather thick layer of greed in the 1980s, and in fact a thick layer of scandalous behavior.
And that's truly unfortunate.

And maybe we can get, I don't know, maybe during the 90s, people who really care about each other and about the society and about the environment can get the country back from the bastards who've been kind of taking advantage of the rest of us.
I don't know.
It depends on whether we've got the guts to do it or not.
Overall, in your opinion, what is the impact of radicals on American society?
Well, again, the term radical is a very vague one for me, and I'm not sure exactly what it means.
I suppose one could approach the question by asking, where are the old radicals of the 1960s?
And of course, some of the greatest ones are not with us anymore.
Jerry Rubin is no longer around.
Tom Hayden is still a congressman in California.
I think that the radicals, I think that there's a basic problem with being a radical, and that is that you have to make a case that's so extreme that its time in play sometimes is very short.
It seems to me that even though the model may seem somewhat simplistic, things do tend to operate in pendulum swings.
And a radical may be, the message of a radical may in fact be only relevant when the pendulum is at the extreme positions.
It doesn't mean we can't learn from these people, but what it usually means is that their position is not one that works over the long run.
It seems to me that people who've really made more of a difference in the long run in the American society have been people who have taken
ideas from radicals from all persuasions, all parts of the political and social spectrum, and found ways of sorting out what was good from what was bad.
And so in this regard, I guess I'm a real pragmatist, trying to find things that work as opposed to trying to find things that fit an ideology.
And one final question.
What do you think the impact of the 1960s is on us now?
Well, I think that's what it is.
I think that we're more experimental and we're probably able to listen to a wider diversity of viewpoints and we're willing to try out things that weren't previously even considered.
I hope that those effects will continue.
I think they'll almost have to, because I think that the 1960s brought in what can only be termed a real cultural revolution.
And I don't mean just in terms of the clothes people wore and how they wore their hair and so on, because a lot of that's gone.
But cultural revolution in the sense of the way that we perceive ourselves

as not so much fixed anymore and not so much as a society that's finished somehow and we just need to do some fine-tuning, but one that really in which active, ongoing experimentation is really important.
I think that's a very rich heritage from the 1960s.
Thank you very, very much.
Thank you.
Hi, I'm Kelly Wood, and this is December 6th, and I'm interviewing Larry Hickman concerning the 60s movement.
